---
description: Two interfaces — Admin Portal (web) and Agent Portal (web)
alwaysApply: true
---

This project has exactly two user-facing interfaces. All features, APIs, and docs must account for them.

## 1. Admin Portal

- **Purpose:** Tenant admins configure and monitor the sales system.
- **Stack:** Next.js + TypeScript (same web app, role-based routes).
- **Scope:** Tenant-wide KPIs dashboard, agent management, lead management, lead flow designer, campaign management, call routing rules, analytics & reports, settings, audit log.
- **Access:** RBAC; Tenant Admin or Super Admin role only.
- **Where:** Served from the same Next.js app under routes like `/admin/*` or `/(dashboard)/admin/*`.

## 2. Agent Portal

- **Purpose:** Sales reps use the portal during and between calls.
- **Stack:** Next.js + TypeScript (same web app, role-based routes).
- **Scope:** Call queue, click-to-call softphone (Twilio), real-time call guidance panel, post-call summary, AI coaching scorecard, deal prediction, red flag alerts, lead detail view, notes & follow-ups.
- **Access:** Agent or Manager role; scoped to assigned leads and own call history.
- **Where:** Served from the same Next.js app under routes like `/agent/*` or `/(dashboard)/agent/*`.

## Rules

- **Backend:** One API surface serves both portals; use RBAC and scopes to distinguish admin vs agent access.
- **Web (Next.js):** Single app that hosts both Admin and Agent Portal; separate routes/layouts and role checks; shared design system (component library) and API client.
- **No mobile app** in this project; both portals are web-only.

Do not:
- Build agent-only flows accessible to non-authenticated users.
- Assume only one "frontend"; there are two logical portals in one app.
- Expose admin-only endpoints (agent management, tenant settings) to agent-role users.
